Gators are not an acceptable form of a face mask. If a student/teacher wears a gator in school it does not protect them or anyone around them!

With this new information, we will not be allowing gators, or anything similar, to be worn at school.

Please remember that this is a very fluid situation. Things will be changing all the time.

Link to the CD on this guidance:
https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/about-face-coverings.html

Thanks for all of your support and cooperation.

The St. Ansgar School District and the City of St. Ansgar have recommended a walking route to and from school in the city of St. Ansgar. This map shows the recommended route and the crossings for Highway 218, 4th and South Main streets. The crosswalks have been painted and stop signs will be placed in these crossings in the morning before school and in the afternoon after school. For the first three weeks Falk Construction’s employees have volunteered to man these crosswalks to help the students learn the route. We look forward to seeing your children on Monday for the beginning of the new school year.

Be sure to check your email for a copy of the map.

Plan for Graduation
The St. Ansgar School District has set July 26, 2020 as our date for graduation. The ceremony will take place at 2:00 p.m. in the high school gym. We ask that all guests enter through the main high school entrance. WE ARE LIMITING ATTENDANCE TO THE GRADUATES AND THEIR FAMILIES AND ARE ASKING FAMILIES TO SIT TOGETHER AND ADHERE TO THE SOCIAL DISTANCING GUIDELINES. The event will be live streamed on the district website for those that are not able to attend.

Following the ceremony, we will be holding a "drive by" receiving line in the high school parking lot east of the high school gym to honor the graduates. Please join us in celebrating our seniors!

The district will continue to follow the guidelines set forth by the Mitchell County Department of Health.

Press Release--Worth County residents only...

Due to the coronavirus the WCDA will be implementing safety measures for our K-12 Gift Card program. The program will start Monday, August 3 thru Friday August 28. Card pick up hours are 8:30-4:00, Monday thru Friday. The following guidelines will be strictly adhered to:
1. No infants, toddlers or children will be allowed in the office. Please make arrangements prior to picking up your cards. There will be no exceptions.
2. Masks will be required for any person coming into the office.
3. Only one parent will be allowed into the office at a time.
4. Social distancing outside of the office is required.
5. If you have any covid symptoms, please send a signed statement saying who can pick your cards up for you. Make sure they send their receipts with you.
We are happy to be able to provide parents with our gift cards, but want everyone to remain safe. Thank you in advance for your help.
Deb Hanson/WCDA

Baseball and softball are here!!! The HS teams begin the season at home on the 15th against the Central Springs Panthers. Game times are--5:30-JV BB, 6:00-Var SB, 7:30-JV SB, and 7:30-Var BB.

There is no admission this summer, but we will be collecting a free will offering for each home event. This money will be put into OUR ATHLETIC FUND!!! It stays here.

Please understand that there will be NO bleachers used this summer. Please bring your own lawn chair, or you may stand. There will be no concession stand. You may bring in your own coolers with appropriate food and drink.

Once here, you need to follow social distancing guidelines. Immediate families may sit together. There needs to be at least 6' between families. Restrooms are open so please be sure to wash hands after use.

The most important thing is to really try and follow the guidelines set forth by the DE, IDPH, IGHSAU, and the IAHSAA. It only takes ONE case of COVID-19 to cancel the season. I would hate for this to happen to our athletes. All of us need this season to take place.

Thank you for you cooperation.

The Stacyville Public Library now has several free resources posted on either our Facebook page or our website that are accessible for anyone to use including Storyline online, Crabtree nonfiction books ( username read and password is free for Crabtree), and Tumblebooks (both fiction and nonfiction books for all grade levels). We also have Gale resources available on our website. If you are a patron of most North Iowa area libraries, you can also download free audiobooks, ebooks, magazines and videos from Bridges. To access Bridges for the Stacyville Library, go to our website and click on Bridges, choose your library, and then enter your library card number to download items. You can always call our library if you need assistance.

post_text: Congratulations to the High School Battle of the Books Team. They competed in an online competition and placed tenth. It was a very close race; the winning team from Newton scored 27 points while our team scored 24. Three points separated the top ten teams. Forty-four teams from Iowa high school participated in this year's online competition. Teams read twenty-eight books and answered questions about those books. Participating in this year's challenge were Bailey Beyer, Jaidyn Beyer, Tianna Charlson, Jessica Horgen and Brenna R. Kruse. Way to go Saints!

post_text:
Positive messages, Part 3

Let Evening Come
By Jane Kenyon

Let the light of late afternoon
shine through chinks in the barn, moving
up the bales as the sun moves down.

Let the cricket take up chafing
as a woman takes up her needles
and her yarn. Let evening come.

Let dew collect on the hoe abandoned
in long grass. Let the stars appear
and the moon disclose her silver horn.

Let the fox go back to its sandy den.
Let the wind die down. Let the shed
go black inside. Let evening come.

To the bottle in the ditch, to the scoop
in the oats, to air in the lung
let evening come.

Let it come, as it will, and don’t
be afraid. God does not leave us
comfortless, so let evening come.

post_text:
Positive messages, Part 2.

--It's going to get harder before it gets easier. But it will get better. You just gotta make it through the hard stuff first.

--Maybe you have to know the darkness before you appreciate the light.

--If you do bare minimum, expect bare minimum results. You want to be great, work to be great. Nothing just happens.

--If something brings you joy and meaning, don't give up just because things get difficult complicated.

--Don't give up because you had a bad day, forgive yourself and do better tomorrow.

--Happiness can be found, even in the darkest of times, if one only remembers to turn on the light.

--You gain strength, courage and confidence by every experience in which you really stop to look fear in the face. You are able to say to yourself, I lived through this horror, I can take the next thing that comes along. You must do the thing that you think you cannot do.

post_text:
Dear Students and Families,

As you may have heard, Governor Reynolds announced yesterday that schools in Iowa should remain closed through April 30 in response to the COVID-19 crisis. While we are disappointed knowing that it will be several more weeks before we see our students, the safety of our community and state comes first.

Our board will review the options outlined by the Iowa Department of Education for continuing learning during the closure, and consider which is the most appropriate path forward for our students, families, and staff. It is our hope to announce a specific plan by April 10, 2020.

We know that you have many questions. Rest assured that as soon as we have more specific information about how we will move forward with learning, we will share it with you. I’m committed to ensuring that every student in the St. Ansgar Community School District receives the education that s/he deserves.

Please don’t hesitate to reach out to me if you have any questions.

Best,
Michael R. Crozier
Superintendent of Schools

post_text:
Starting this Thursday, March 19th, we will begin offering FREE breakfast and lunch to students. Meals will be dropped off in the mornings at regular bus stops at normal bus times. Students simply need to meet the bus/van at the normal time and place to receive a lunch and breakfast. Meals will be delivered Monday-Friday.

ANY student is eligible to receive meals. If you would like to sign up to receive meals, please contact the school by phone (641-713-4720 or 641-713-2331 or via email dpeterson@st-ansgar.k12.ia.us or jdemaris@st-ansgar.k12.ia.us by 3:30 PM on Tuesday. We apologize for the short notice, but we must get appropriate supplies ordered to begin this week. You can sign up at any time after this, but we need these numbers to start on Thursday. Once you have signed up, you will continue to receive meals during this time of school closure.

If at any time you need to self-quarantine due to the COVID-19 virus, please let us know so we can plan accordingly.

Hey Saints fans. Come join us on Wednesday morning at 7:15 for a community pep rally in the MS gym as we send our Girls basketball team to the state basketball tournament.

Come support the Saints Girls Basketball team at state this Wednesday at 3:15 in Des Moines. We will be running a pep bus for students in grades 7-12. The cost to ride the bus is $5 and admission is $10. The bus will depart at 11:30 am from the middle school parking lot. Please sign up in the office by noon on Tuesday. The $15 will need to be paid at the school in order to purchase tickets in advance.

There will also be a community charter bus that will be going to the game. This is for high school students and older without an adult. Anyone younger than high school wanting to ride, must be accompanied by an adult. There is space for 55 people to ride the bus. To sign up, please call 641-832-8255. The charter bus is free to ride and will be leaving from South Square at 11:30 Wednesday morning.

Tomorrow night the STA girls play Central Elkader at New Hampton with a trip to the state tournament on the line. Game time is 7:00PM.

The STA girls are coming off an exciting, intense victory over Clarksville last Friday, 67-64. Our parents, fans and student body did a fantastic job of cheering on the girls. We need that again tomorrow night.

The last time the STA girls played in the state tourney was 2001. I would say that has been long enough between trips to DSM.

The captains have chosen the theme of USA for dress tomorrow night. So, come to the game, be loud, dress in red, white and blue. The girls' would love to see the STA side be packed and as loud as ever in support of the Saints.

Be there, be loud!! Let's Go SAINTS!!!

A big thank you to the community members that helped with the 8th grade creative problem solving projects.
Ty Demaris/ Demaris Hardware
Wes Hardy/ Mitchell County EMT
Meagan Steinberg/ Saints Stone
Dave Juhl / St. Ansgar Landscaping
Ed Kleinwort / St. Ansgar Mills
Sherrie Hansen / Blue Belle Inn
John Henaman / Food Center
Steph Beaver / St. Ansgar School Lunch Program
These business partners shared potential problems in their businesses. Some issues shared included: the best way to advertise, when is an appropriate time to call 911, how to increase sales, and how to find dependable employees. After listening to these issues, students chose a problem and worked in small groups to come up with creative solutions. These business partners were invited to the classroom to listen to the creative problem solving presentations and shared some feedback with the students. It was a great learning experience!

- We will be having a Community Pep Rally on Thursday, Sept. 19th, at 7 p.m., in the MS gym. All are welcome to attend.

- The Homecoming Parade will begin at 2:15 on Friday, Sept. 20th.

- The parade will start at the high school, go west on 8th street, turn north on Washington (going past the old elementary), turn east on 4th street, and then return to the high school on Train Lane. We would then have the King & Queen Coronation at the football field (at approximately 2:45). If it rains, the coronation will take place in the HS Gym.

- And, most importantly, the game (vs. Postville) starts at 7 p.m.

post_text: The St. Ansgar 5th grade class joined the 6th graders for lunch today so they could experience how middle school lunch works. The 6th graders were great mentors and helped the 5th graders through the line, and also gave them some good advice as they all ate together. We are excited for the 5th graders to join us as middle schoolers next fall!

post_text: Bringing History to Life: Here the 4th graders are debating against each other as Patriots and Loyalists trying to decide whether to separate from Great Britain or remain connected. We had a group of second graders and third graders come observe and see what it was all about! Each side presented arguments as well as rebuttals against the arguments. Lot's of fun was had by all!

post_text: Thirty members of the St. Ansgar senior class participated in the 2019 St. Ansgar Scholarship Fund phonathon fundraiser on Thursday night. Over $5000.00 in scholarship pledges was raised by the group in just three hours. Any community members who would like to donate but did not receive a call can drop off donations at the high school or at St. Ansgar State Bank. A big thank you to the residents of St. Ansgar, Stacyville and Grafton and surrounding communities for your continued support!

The Northeast Area Special Olympics of Iowa were held at the UNI Dome Sunday. Great day! Saints team results in individual heats:

Emma Enzenauer - 2nd place in softball throw, 3rd in 50 M dash
Jesse Kruse - 1st in ball throw, 2nd in 50 M dash
Jaret Kruse - 3rd in ball throw, 4th in 50 M dash
Chris Sprandel - 4th in ball throw, 3rd in 50 M dash
Jase James - 1st in ball throw , 1st in 50 M dash
Kara Lawrence - 1st in ball throw, 1st in 25 M walk

Next is state competition at ISU, Ames May 23-24th.
